uires intrinsic factor for absorption","Absorbed via active transport in large intestine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin E is a fat-soluble vitamin that \u003Cstrong\u003Erequires bile acids for absorption in the small intestine\u003C/strong\u003E. Like other fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, K), vitamin E requires micelle formation with bile acids for efficient absorption across the intestinal epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsorbed directly through gastric mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E - Fat-soluble vitamins are not absorbed in the stomach\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires intrinsic factor for absorption\u003C/strong\u003E - Intrinsic factor is required for vitamin B12 absorption, not vitamin E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsorbed via active transport in large intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - Vitamin E absorption occurs in the small intestine, not the large intestine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires calcium for absorption in duodenum\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium is not required for vitamin E absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConditions that impair bile acid secretion or fat absorption, such as cholestatic liver disease or cystic fibrosis, can lead to vitamin E deficiency due to malabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin E is a fat-soluble vitamin primarily absorbed in the small intestine requiring bile acids for absorption","Vitamin E functions as an antioxidant protecting cell membranes from oxidative damage","Deficiency of vitamin E can lead to neurological symptoms and haemolytic anaemia"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationsh